{"title_page": "Montrose and Bervie Railway", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox rail\n| name = The Montrose and<br>Bervie Railway\n| logo_filename     = \n| logo_size         = \n| system_map        = \n| map_caption       = \n| marks             = \n| locale            = [[Scotland]] \n| start_year        = 1865\n| end_year          = 1966\n| predecessor_line  = \n| successor_line    = \n| gauge             = {{RailGauge|uksg}}\n| length            = \n| hq_city           =  \n| map = {{The Montrose & Bervie Railway|inline=1}}\n}}\n[[File:Montrose (Cal) station.jpg|thumb|right|Ex Caledonian Railway Montrose station in 1960]]\n[[File:St Cyrus.jpg|thumb|right|St Cyrus railway station with Scottish rail tour in 1960]]\n\nThe '''Montrose and Bervie Railway''' was a [[Scotland|Scottish]] railway. When the [[Aberdeen Railway]] opened in 1850, the coastal settlements north of [[Montrose, Angus|Montrose]] were not linked in, and local interests promoted a branch line from Montrose to [[Bervie]]. They found it impossible to raise capital at first, but from 1861 the larger railways were promoting new connections around [[Aberdeen]], and the [[Great North of Scotland Railway]] (GNoSR) decided that the Bervie line would give it a route to the south.\n\nThat scheme did not proceed, but the GNoSR had put money in, and the simple branch line opened, in 1865.\n\nIt was absorbed by the [[North British Railway]] in 1881, who also thought it might give them a springboard towards Aberdeen; that scheme too failed to materialise, and the line remained a quiet backwater.\n\nRoad transport spelt doom for the sparsely trafficked line, and it closed in 1951.\n\n==History==\n\n===The first railway to Montrose===\nIn 1848, the [[Aberdeen Railway]] opened its line from Guthrie, between Arbroath and Forfar, to Montrose; a shortage of capital delayed its extension to Aberdeen for a while, but after some difficulty it opened to Ferryhill in 1850. The main line ran inland, however, and Montrose was at the end of a stub branch. The coastal communities further north saw the benefits of a railway connection to other villages, and they pressed the Aberdeen Railway, and its successor the [[Scottish North Eastern Railway]] (SNER), to build a branch northwards along the coast.\n\n===An independent concern===\nThese approaches were unsuccessful and the larger companies had other priorities. At length the local people promoted their own branch line, and they obtained their authorising Act of Parliament for the ''Montrose and Bervie Railway'' on 3 July 1860. The line was to be 12&nbsp;miles (19&nbsp;km) long and authorised capital was \u00a370,000.{{sfn|Carter|1959|p=}}{{page needed|date=July 2018}}{{sfn|Simms|1985|p=}}{{page needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nThe Act ''authorised'' the capital but the company had to raise the money themselves, and this proved extremely difficult. In fact two years of strenuous attempts to secure subscriptions were almost completely fruitless, and it appeared likely that the scheme would have to be abandoned.\n\n[[File:Bervie rly & snjr.gif|thumb|The Great North of Scotland Railway plan to use the Bervie line]]However in 1861 a new main line railway was floated, the ''Scottish Northern Junction Railway'', which would connect Kintore, on the [[Great North of Scotland Railway]] (GNoSR) line near Inverurie, with the SNER at Limpet Mill near Stonehaven. It had been a sore point for several years that the GNoSR and the SNER had no through connection at Aberdeen, the GNoSR being content to transfer southwards goods to coastal shipping at Aberdeen; at a stroke a highly useful through line would be created, taking away substantial income from the GNoSR.{{sfn|Thomas|1976|pages=146\u2013154}}\n\n===Funded by the GNoSR===\nThe GNoSR was alarmed by this development, but it saw that if the Montrose and Bervie line were built, it could build extensions northwards and southwards to link Stonehaven and Arbroath; if it could secure running powers over the SNER as well, it would have access from its network to Dundee. The GNoSR bought up substantial blocks of M&BR shares, and a revised route had to be surveyed, converting the planned coastal branch line to a main line, with better gradients, easier curves, and a location at Bervie from which the line could run northwards.\n\nA Bill was presented to Parliament for the 1863 session, with the north and south extensions included: together they were longer than the original route. Disaster befell the company in Parliament, for the scheme was thrown out.{{sfn|Thomas|1976|pages=146\u2013154}}{{sfn|Thomas|Turnock|1989|pages=167 and 168}}\n\n===A local line after all===\n[[File:Bervie rly 1869.gif|thumb|The Montrose and Bervie Railway as built]]Naturally the GNoSR lost interest in the little backwater railway so far from its own network; but now the line had some share capital and the original Act of Parliament, and it set about constructing the line as originally intended. By the summer of 1865 the line was nearing completion, and enquiries were made of [[R and W Hawthorn]], who had purchased the Leith Engine Works, for a locomotive for their line, but the price must have been discouraging. The Company asked the GNoSR to work the line, but this was refused, and finally the SNER worked the line. It opened on 1 November 1865. The trains used the SNER station at Montrose, joining the SNER at Broomfield Junction. (The [[Caledonian Railway]] absorbed the SNER in 1866 and took over the working.){{sfn|Simms|1985|p=}}{{page needed|date=July 2018}}{{sfn|Ross|2014a|pages=93 and 152}}\n\nIn the first nine months of operation an operating surplus of \u00a3152 was achieved, but this was without allowing for the toll charge for the use of the Montrose station and approach railway. At over \u00a3330 for six months alone, this turned the figures into a major loss. The Company asked the Caledonian to reduce the charge, but when this was declined, the Bervie Company established a station at Broomfield Road, just on its side of the junction, and terminated its trains there. It arranged road cartage to and from Montrose.{{sfn|Smith|Anderson|1997}}{{page needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nThis seems to have motivated compromise in the Caledonian, and a reduced toll charge of \u00a3150 annually was agreed; trains resumed running to Montrose (Caledonian Railway) from 8 August 1866. The Bervie directors undertook to close the Broomfield station permanently, which they did from 1 February 1867.{{sfn|Thomas|1976|pages=146\u2013154}}{{sfn|Thomas|Turnock|1989|pages=167 and 168}}\n\n===Now sponsored by the North British Railway===\n[[File:Bervie rly & nbr.gif|thumb|The North British Railway plan to use the Bervie Railway]]The line had nearly become part of a GNoSR trunk route in 1863, and now another suitor appeared. The [[North British Railway]] (NBR) was operating a rather disjointed service between Edinburgh and Aberdeen by ferries across the [[Firth of Forth]] and [[Firth of Tay]], and then over the Caledonian Railway via Arbroath and Stonehaven. Parliament had granted the NBR running powers over large parts of the northern section of the Caledonian Railway, in order to encourage competition. Nonetheless, this dependency on a competitor was hardly a satisfactory arrangement, and the NBR aspired to establish a route controlled by itself. Bridging the Forth and Tay was feasible, although expensive. Getting from Dundee to Arbroath would be done over the [[Dundee and Arbroath Railway]] which was to be operated jointly. A new NBR line from Arbroath to near Stonehaven could use the Montrose and Bervie line, saving construction costs.\n\nThe Caledonian had a contract with the M&BR to work the line until 1873, and fearing the NBR incursion, negotiated to extend that for a further eight years, frustrating the NBR plans.{{sfn|Simms|1985|p=}}{{page needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nThe Bervie line was utterly impoverished, and yet this scheme was received coldly by many local interests, who preferred retaining independence, but these reservations were overcome and the Montrose and Bervie Railway was absorbed by the North British Railway on 1 October 1881.{{sfn|Carter|1959|p=}}{{page needed|date=July 2018}} (This was originally intended to be 1 August; the NBR paid 65% of the face value of M&BR stock and assumed the company's mortgage debt of \u00a318,000.{{sfn|Ross|2014b|pages=90, 91 and 120}} The Caledonian Railway was permitted to retain running powers. The Bervie line trains now ran to the NBR station at Montrose.\n\nThe NBR had sponsored a nominally independent line from Arbroath to Montrose (the [[North British, Arbroath and Montrose Railway]]), which obtained its authorising Act of Parliament on 13 July 1871, capital \u00a3171,580. There was some delay in construction, but it opened to goods traffic in 1881, and to passengers in 1883.{{sfn|Carter|1959|p=}}{{page needed|date=July 2018}}{{sfn|Ross|2014b|pages=90, 91 and 120}} It had its own station at Montrose, and joined the Caledonian main line at Kinnaber Junction, a few miles north of Montrose. However, the development of the Bervie line, and the new construction at its north end onward to Stonehaven, never took place.\n\nWhen the North British, Arbroath and Montrose Railway opened its line, a spur was provided (authorised by an Act of 1872{{sfn|Simms|1985|p=}}{{page needed|date=July 2018}}) connecting that company's main line at Montrose North Junction (immediately north of Montrose NBR station) to Broomfield Road Junction, giving access to the Bervie line.{{sfn|Smith|Anderson|1997}}{{page needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nFrom 2 August 1897 the Caledonian Railway started operating its own train services on the Bervie line, exercising the running powers already granted. This was hardly a commercial move, and was simply in retaliation for an imagined act of bad faith elsewhere by the NBR. Passengers on the line therefore had CR trains to the CR Montrose station and NBR trains to the NBR station. There was simply not enough traffic on the line to sustain this, and Caledonian trains stopped running from 1 October 1898. However, there were local protests at this, and Caledonian goods services quickly resumed (on 17 October), but were finally discontinued from June 1899.{{sfn|Simms|1985|p=}}{{page needed|date=July 2018}}{{sfn|Thomas|1976|pages=146\u2013154}}{{sfn|Ross|2014a|pages=93 and 152}}\n\nThe line was now simply a remote coastal branch line of the North British Railway.\n\n===The twentieth century===\nIn 1913 the [[Royal Flying Corps]] established its first operational airfield at Broomfield Farm, adjacent to the Bervie line immediately north of Broomfield Junction. On the formation of the [[Royal Air Force]] the location became [[RAF Montrose]]. The site was used for military purposes almost continuously until closure in 1952. There was a short siding, named \"Aerodrome Siding\" facing from the Bervie direction at the north end of the site at Wardhouse Road. During [[World War II]] an aircraft approaching struck and demolished part of Broomfield Junction signal box.{{sfn|Smith|Anderson|1997}}{{page needed|date=July 2018}}<ref name = os>Ordance Survey Maps, 1924 (1:2,500) and 1928 (1:10,560)</ref>\n\nIn 1923 the North British Railway was a constituent of the new [[London and North Eastern Railway]], following the grouping of the railways of Great Britain under the [[Railways Act 1921]]. The Caledonian Railway was a constituent of the [[London Midland and Scottish Railway]].\n\nBy 1951 road passenger and goods services in the area had become dominant, and the line was closed to passengers. A daily goods train continued to run until 23 May 1966 when the line was closed completely.{{sfn|Smith|Anderson|1997}}{{page needed|date=July 2018}}\n\n==Train service==\nThe passenger train service in 1895 consisted of six trains each way daily, with an extra Fridays only service; the journey time was typically 38 to 40 minutes.{{sfn|Bradshaw|1895|page=}}{{page needed|date=July 2018}} By 1922 the service had reduced to three daily with an additional Saturday trip.{{sfn|Bradshaw|1922| page=}}{{page needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nIn 1938 there were three daily return trips with an additional Friday train from Inverbervie to Montrose.{{sfn|Bradshaw|1938|page=}}{{page needed|date=July 2018}}\n\n[[File:North Esk Water Railway Bridge - geograph.org.uk - 988062.jpg|thumb|right|North West Water railway Bridge crosses the River North Esk]]\n\n==Present-day remains==\nIn many places the track bed can still be seen. The northern section is now a well surfaced footpath and is part of the [[National Cycle Network]].\n\n==Topography==\nThe line ran Broomfield Road Junction to Bervie; passenger trains generally ran from and to Montrose. The line opened on 1 November 1865, and closed to passengers on 1 October 1951.\n\nLocations on the line:\n\n* ''Broomfield Road Junction''; the line diverged from the Caledonian Railway;\n* Broomfield Road Junction station; also known as Broomfield Road; opened with the M&BR line on 1 November 1865;{{refn|group=note|Butt says{{sfn|Butt|1995|page=}}{{page needed|date=July 2018}} the station opened when the Aberdeen Railway opened its main line in 1850, but this is a mistake; the Aberdeen Company did not have a station at the location; see the 25 inch Ordnance Survey map ''Forfar Sheet XXVIII.14'' surveyed 1862; also ''Bradshaw'' for 1850 which shows no station there. Smith says{{sfn|Smith|Anderson|1997|page=32}} that it opened in August 1866 or immediately after.}}{{sfn|Bradshaw|1850|page=}}{{page needed|date=July 2018}}\n* North Water Bridge; opened July 1866;\n* St Cyrus;\n* Lauriston;\n* Johnshaven;\n* Birnie Road Siding; opened November 1866; a very limited Fridays-only train service operated for most of the location's existence; Friday was market day in Montrose;<ref name = vision>{{cite web| url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/place/16420| website=Vision of Britain through time| title=Montrose Angus| publisher=University of Portsmouth}}</ref>\n* Gourdon;\n* Bervie; renamed Inverbervie 5 July 1926.{{sfn|Quick|2002|page=}}{{page needed|date=July 2018}}{{sfn|Cobb|2003|page=}}{{page needed|date=July 2018}}{{sfn|Butt|1995|page=}}{{page needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nA major engineering feature on the line was the 11 arch North Water bridge crossing the [[River North Esk]] which still stands today.{{sfn|Smith|Anderson|1997}}{{page needed|date=July 2018}}<ref name = northwater>{{cite web| url=http://www.forgottenrelics.co.uk/bridges/gallery/northwater.html| title=North Water Bridge| website=Forgotten Relics}}</ref>\n\nSmith describes the line:\n\n<blockquote>It was a very scenic stretch of railway, beginning at Broomfield Junction, north of Montrose, and striding across the North Esk near Kinnaber by means of a high stone viaduct. After a cliff top section to St Cyrus, the line wandered inland for a while before descending to the rocky shore at Johnshaven. The track then curved round the back of Gourdon village and continued along the coast to a terminus close to Bervie Bay. Architecturally the stations were undistinguished: all seven of them having basic single-storey buildings with horizontal timber planking and brick chimneys.{{sfn|Smith|Anderson|1997}}{{page needed|date=July 2018}}</blockquote>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist | group  = note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n* {{cite book| title=Bradshaw's General Steam Navigation and Railway Guide| orig-year=March 1850| edition=reprint| publisher=Middleton Press| location=Midhurst| year=2012| isbn=978-1-908174-13-0| ref=Bradshaw1850}}\n* {{cite book| title=Bradshaw's General Steam Navigation and Railway Guide| orig-year=December 1895| edition=reprint| publisher=Middleton Press| location=Midhurst| year=2011| isbn=978-1-908174-11-6| ref=Bradshaw1895}}\n* {{cite book| title=Bradshaw's General Railway and Steam Navigation Guide| orig-year=July 1922| edition=reprint| publisher=Guild Publishing| location=London| year=1985| ref=Bradshaw1922}}\n* {{cite book| title=Bradshaw's July 1938 Railway Guide| publisher=David and Charles (Publishers) Limited| location=Newton Abbot| year=1969| isbn=0-7153-4686-5| ref=Bradshaw1938}}\n* {{cite book| first=R.V.J.| last=Butt| title=The Directory of Railway Stations| publisher=Patrick Stephens Limited| location=Sparkford| year=1995| isbn=1-85260-508-1}}\n* {{cite book| first=E.F.| last=Carter| title=An Historical Geography of the Railways of the British Isles| publisher=Cassell| location=London| year=1959}}\n* {{cite book| first=Col M.H.| last=Cobb| title=The Railways of Great Britain \u2013 A Historical Atlas| publisher=Ian Allan Publishing Limited| location=Shepperton| year=2003| isbn=07110-3003-0}}\n* {{cite book| first=M.E.| last=Quick| title=Railway Passenger Stations in England Scotland and Wales\u2014A Chronology| publisher=The Railway and Canal Historical Society| year=2002}}\n* {{cite book| first=David| last=Ross| title=The Caledonian: Scotland's Imperial Railway: A History| publisher=Stenlake Publishing Limited| location=Catrine| year=2014a| isbn=978-1840-335842}}\n* {{cite book| first=David| last=Ross| title=The North British Railway: A History| publisher=Stenlake Publishing Limited| location=Catrine| year=2014b| isbn=978-1-84033-647-4}}\n* {{cite book| first=W.| last=Simms| title=Railways of Brechin| publisher=Angus District Libraries and Museums| year=1985}}\n* {{cite book| first1=W.A.C.| last1=Smith| first2=Paul| last2=Anderson| title=An Illustrated History of Tayside's Railways, Dundee and Perth| publisher=Irwell Press| location=Clophill| year=1997| isbn=1-871608-73-2}}\n* {{cite book| first=John| last=Thomas| title=Forgotten Railways Scotland| publisher=David & Charles| location=Newton Abbot| year=1976| isbn=0-7153-7185-1}}\n* {{cite book| first1=John| last1=Thomas| first2=David| last2=Turnock| title=A Regional History of the Railways of Great Britain: Volume 15: North of Scotland| publisher=David & Charles| location=Newton Abbot| year=1989|isbn=0-946537-03-8}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book| last=Holland| first=Julian| year=2010| title=Discovering Scotland's Lost Local Lines| pages=91-99| publisher=Waverley Books| isbn=978-1-84934-018-2}}\n*Mitchell, Mike (2015), The Montrose & Bervie Railway, a study of transport in south-east Kincardineshire, 1770\u20131966. {{ISBN|9781 89988996 9}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.railbrit.co.uk/Montrose_and_Bervie_Railway/frame.htm Railscot on Montrose and Bervie Railway]\n \n{{Historical Scottish railway companies}}\n\n[[Category:Closed railway lines in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Railway lines in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Early Scottish railway companies]]\n[[Category:Standard gauge railways in Scotland]]\n[[Category:North British Railway]]\n[[Category:Pre-grouping British railway companies]]\n[[Category:Railway lines opened in 1865]]\n[[Category:1865 establishments in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Railway lines closed in 1966]]\n[[Category:British companies established in 1860]] \n[[Category:Railway companies established in 1860]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox rail\n| name = The Montrose and<br>Bervie Railway\n| logo_filename     = \n| logo_size         = \n| system_map        = \n| map_caption       = \n| marks             = \n| locale            = [[Scotland]] \n| start_year        = 1865\n| end_year          = 1966\n| predecessor_line  = \n| successor_line    = \n| gauge             = {{RailGauge|uksg}}\n| length            = \n| hq_city           =  \n| map = {{The Montrose & Bervie Railway|inline=1}}\n}}\n[[File:Montrose (Cal) station.jpg|thumb|right|Ex Caledonian Railway Montrose station in 1960]]\n[[File:St Cyrus.jpg|thumb|right|St Cyrus railway station with Scottish rail tour in 1960]]\n\nThe '''Montrose and Bervie Railway''' was a [[Scotland|Scottish]] railway. When the [[Aberdeen Railway]] opened in 1850, the coastal settlements north of [[Montrose, Angus|Montrose]] were not linked in, and local interests promoted a branch line from Montrose to [[Bervie]]. They found it impossible to raise capital at first, but from 1861 the larger railways were promoting new connections around [[Aberdeen]], and the [[Great North of Scotland Railway]] (GNoSR) decided that the Bervie line would give it a route to the south.\n\nThat scheme did not proceed, but the GNoSR had put money in, and the simple branch line opened, in 1865.\n\nIt was absorbed by the [[North British Railway]] in 1881, who also thought it might give them a springboard towards Aberdeen; that scheme too failed to materialise, and the line remained a quiet backwater.\n\nRoad transport spelt doom for the sparsely trafficked line, and it closed in 1951.\n\n==History==\n\n===The first railway to Montrose===\nIn 1848, the [[Aberdeen Railway]] opened its line from Guthrie, between Arbroath and Forfar, to Montrose; a shortage of capital delayed its extension to Aberdeen for a while, but after some difficulty it opened to Ferryhill in 1850. The main line ran inland, however, and Montrose was at the end of a stub branch. The coastal communities further north saw the benefits of a railway connection to other villages, and they pressed the Aberdeen Railway, and its successor the [[Scottish North Eastern Railway]] (SNER), to build a branch northwards along the coast.\n\n===An independent concern===\nThese approaches were unsuccessful and the larger companies had other priorities. At length the local people promoted their own branch line, and they obtained their authorising Act of Parliament for the ''Montrose and Bervie Railway'' on 3 July 1860. The line was to be 12&nbsp;miles (19&nbsp;km) long and authorised capital was \u00a370,000.{{sfn|Carter|1959|p=}}{{page needed|date=July 2018}}{{sfn|Simms|1985|p=}}{{page needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nThe Act ''authorised'' the capital but the company had to raise the money themselves, and this proved extremely difficult. In fact two years of strenuous attempts to secure subscriptions were almost completely fruitless, and it appeared likely that the scheme would have to be abandoned.\n\n[[File:Bervie rly & snjr.gif|thumb|The Great North of Scotland Railway plan to use the Bervie line]]However in 1861 a new main line railway was floated, the ''Scottish Northern Junction Railway'', which would connect Kintore, on the [[Great North of Scotland Railway]] (GNoSR) line near Inverurie, with the SNER at Limpet Mill near Stonehaven. It had been a sore point for several years that the GNoSR and the SNER had no through connection at Aberdeen, the GNoSR being content to transfer southwards goods to coastal shipping at Aberdeen; at a stroke a highly useful through line would be created, taking away substantial income from the GNoSR.{{sfn|Thomas|1976|pages=146\u2013154}}\n\n===Funded by the GNoSR===\nThe GNoSR was alarmed by this development, but it saw that if the Montrose and Bervie line were built, it could build extensions northwards and southwards to link Stonehaven and Arbroath; if it could secure running powers over the SNER as well, it would have access from its network to Dundee. The GNoSR bought up substantial blocks of M&BR shares, and a revised route had to be surveyed, converting the planned coastal branch line to a main line, with better gradients, easier curves, and a location at Bervie from which the line could run northwards.\n\nA Bill was presented to Parliament for the 1863 session, with the north and south extensions included: together they were longer than the original route. Disaster befell the company in Parliament, for the scheme was thrown out.{{sfn|Thomas|1976|pages=146\u2013154}}{{sfn|Thomas|Turnock|1989|pages=167 and 168}}\n\n===A local line after all===\n[[File:Bervie rly 1869.gif|thumb|The Montrose and Bervie Railway as built]]Naturally the GNoSR lost interest in the little backwater railway so far from its own network; but now the line had some share capital and the original Act of Parliament, and it set about constructing the line as originally intended. By the summer of 1865 the line was nearing completion, and enquiries were made of [[R and W Hawthorn]], who had purchased the Leith Engine Works, for a locomotive for their line, but the price must have been discouraging. The Company asked the GNoSR to work the line, but this was refused, and finally the SNER worked the line. It opened on 1 November 1865. The trains used the SNER station at Montrose, joining the SNER at Broomfield Junction. (The [[Caledonian Railway]] absorbed the SNER in 1866 and took over the working.){{sfn|Simms|1985|p=}}{{page needed|date=July 2018}}{{sfn|Ross|2014a|pages=93 and 152}}\n\nIn the first nine months of operation an operating surplus of \u00a3152 was achieved, but this was without allowing for the toll charge for the use of the Montrose station and approach railway. At over \u00a3330 for six months alone, this turned the figures into a major loss. The Company asked the Caledonian to reduce the charge, but when this was declined, the Bervie Company established a station at Broomfield Road, just on its side of the junction, and terminated its trains there. It arranged road cartage to and from Montrose.{{sfn|Smith|Anderson|1997}}{{page needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nThis seems to have motivated compromise in the Caledonian, and a reduced toll charge of \u00a3150 annually was agreed; trains resumed running to Montrose (Caledonian Railway) from 8 August 1866. The Bervie directors undertook to close the Broomfield station permanently, which they did from 1 February 1867.{{sfn|Thomas|1976|pages=146\u2013154}}{{sfn|Thomas|Turnock|1989|pages=167 and 168}}\n\n===Now sponsored by the North British Railway===\n[[File:Bervie rly & nbr.gif|thumb|The North British Railway plan to use the Bervie Railway]]The line had nearly become part of a GNoSR trunk route in 1863, and now another suitor appeared. The [[North British Railway]] (NBR) was operating a rather disjointed service between Edinburgh and Aberdeen by ferries across the [[Firth of Forth]] and [[Firth of Tay]], and then over the Caledonian Railway via Arbroath and Stonehaven. Parliament had granted the NBR running powers over large parts of the northern section of the Caledonian Railway, in order to encourage competition. Nonetheless, this dependency on a competitor was hardly a satisfactory arrangement, and the NBR aspired to establish a route controlled by itself. Bridging the Forth and Tay was feasible, although expensive. Getting from Dundee to Arbroath would be done over the [[Dundee and Arbroath Railway]] which was to be operated jointly. A new NBR line from Arbroath to near Stonehaven could use the Montrose and Bervie line, saving construction costs.\n\nThe Caledonian had a contract with the M&BR to work the line until 1873, and fearing the NBR incursion, negotiated to extend that for a further eight years, frustrating the NBR plans.{{sfn|Simms|1985|p=}}{{page needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nThe Bervie line was utterly impoverished, and yet this scheme was received coldly by many local interests, who preferred retaining independence, but these reservations were overcome and the Montrose and Bervie Railway was absorbed by the North British Railway on 1 October 1881.{{sfn|Carter|1959|p=}}{{page needed|date=July 2018}} (This was originally intended to be 1 August; the NBR paid 65% of the face value of M&BR stock and assumed the company's mortgage debt of \u00a318,000.{{sfn|Ross|2014b|pages=90, 91 and 120}} The Caledonian Railway was permitted to retain running powers. The Bervie line trains now ran to the NBR station at Montrose.\n\nThe NBR had sponsored a nominally independent line from Arbroath to Montrose (the [[North British, Arbroath and Montrose Railway]]), which obtained its authorising Act of Parliament on 13 July 1871, capital \u00a3171,580. There was some delay in construction, but it opened to goods traffic in 1881, and to passengers in 1883.{{sfn|Carter|1959|p=}}{{page needed|date=July 2018}}{{sfn|Ross|2014b|pages=90, 91 and 120}} It had its own station at Montrose, and joined the Caledonian main line at Kinnaber Junction, a few miles north of Montrose. However, the development of the Bervie line, and the new construction at its north end onward to Stonehaven, never took place.\n\nWhen the North British, Arbroath and Montrose Railway opened its line, a spur was provided (authorised by an Act of 1872{{sfn|Simms|1985|p=}}{{page needed|date=July 2018}}) connecting that company's main line at Montrose North Junction (immediately north of Montrose NBR station) to Broomfield Road Junction, giving access to the Bervie line.{{sfn|Smith|Anderson|1997}}{{page needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nFrom 2 August 1897 the Caledonian Railway started operating its own train services on the Bervie line, exercising the running powers already granted. This was hardly a commercial move, and was simply in retaliation for an imagined act of bad faith elsewhere by the NBR. Passengers on the line therefore had CR trains to the CR Montrose station and NBR trains to the NBR station. There was simply not enough traffic on the line to sustain this, and Caledonian trains stopped running from 1 October 1898. However, there were local protests at this, and Caledonian goods services quickly resumed (on 17 October), but were finally discontinued from June 1899.{{sfn|Simms|1985|p=}}{{page needed|date=July 2018}}{{sfn|Thomas|1976|pages=146\u2013154}}{{sfn|Ross|2014a|pages=93 and 152}}\n\nThe line was now simply a remote coastal branch line of the North British Railway.\n\n===The twentieth century===\nIn 1913 the [[Royal Flying Corps]] established its first operational airfield at Broomfield Farm, adjacent to the Bervie line immediately north of Broomfield Junction. On the formation of the [[Royal Air Force]] the location became [[RAF Montrose]]. The site was used for military purposes almost continuously until closure in 1952. There was a short siding, named \"Aerodrome Siding\" facing from the Bervie direction at the north end of the site at Wardhouse Road. During [[World War II]] an aircraft approaching struck and demolished part of Broomfield Junction signal box.{{sfn|Smith|Anderson|1997}}{{page needed|date=July 2018}}<ref name = os>Ordance Survey Maps, 1924 (1:2,500) and 1928 (1:10,560)</ref>\n\nIn 1923 the North British Railway was a constituent of the new [[London and North Eastern Railway]], following the grouping of the railways of Great Britain under the [[Railways Act 1921]]. The Caledonian Railway was a constituent of the [[London Midland and Scottish Railway]].\n\nBy 1951 road passenger and goods services in the area had become dominant, and the line was closed to passengers. A daily goods train continued to run until 23 May 1966 when the line was closed completely.{{sfn|Smith|Anderson|1997}}{{page needed|date=July 2018}}\n\n==Train service==\nThe passenger train service in 1895 consisted of six trains each way daily, with an extra Fridays only service; the journey time was typically 38 to 40 minutes.{{sfn|Bradshaw|1895|page=}}{{page needed|date=July 2018}} By 1922 the service had reduced to three daily with an additional Saturday trip.{{sfn|Bradshaw|1922| page=}}{{page needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nIn 1938 there were three daily return trips with an additional Friday train from Inverbervie to Montrose.{{sfn|Bradshaw|1938|page=}}{{page needed|date=July 2018}}\n\n[[File:North Esk Water Railway Bridge - geograph.org.uk - 988062.jpg|thumb|right|North West Water railway Bridge crosses the River North Esk]]\n\n==Present-day remains==\nIn many places the track bed can still be seen. The northern section is now a well surfaced footpath and is part of the [[National Cycle Network]].\n\n==Topography==\nThe line ran Broomfield Road Junction to Bervie; passenger trains generally ran from and to Montrose. The line opened on 1 November 1865, and closed to passengers on 1 October 1951.\n\nLocations on the line:\n\n* ''Broomfield Road Junction''; the line diverged from the Caledonian Railway;\n* Broomfield Road Junction station; also known as Broomfield Road; opened with the M&BR line on 1 November 1865;{{refn|group=note|Butt says{{sfn|Butt|1995|page=}}{{page needed|date=July 2018}} the station opened when the Aberdeen Railway opened its main line in 1850, but this is a mistake; the Aberdeen Company did not have a station at the location; see the 25 inch Ordnance Survey map ''Forfar Sheet XXVIII.14'' surveyed 1862; also ''Bradshaw'' for 1850 which shows no station there. Smith says{{sfn|Smith|Anderson|1997|page=32}} that it opened in August 1866 or immediately after.}}{{sfn|Bradshaw|1850|page=}}{{page needed|date=July 2018}}\n* North Water Bridge; opened July 1866;\n* St Cyrus;\n* Lauriston;\n* Johnshaven;\n* Birnie Road Siding; opened November 1866; a very limited Fridays-only train service operated for most of the location's existence; Friday was market day in Montrose;<ref name = vision>{{cite web| url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/place/16420| website=Vision of Britain through time| title=Montrose Angus| publisher=University of Portsmouth}}</ref>\n* Gourdon;\n* Bervie; renamed Inverbervie 5 July 1926.{{sfn|Quick|2002|page=}}{{page needed|date=July 2018}}{{sfn|Cobb|2003|page=}}{{page needed|date=July 2018}}{{sfn|Butt|1995|page=}}{{page needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nA major engineering feature on the line was the 11 arch North Water bridge crossing the [[River North Esk]] which still stands today.{{sfn|Smith|Anderson|1997}}{{page needed|date=July 2018}}<ref name = northwater>{{cite web| url=http://www.forgottenrelics.co.uk/bridges/gallery/northwater.html| title=North Water Bridge| website=Forgotten Relics}}</ref>\n\nSmith describes the line:\n\n<blockquote>It was a very scenic stretch of railway, beginning at Broomfield Junction, north of Montrose, and striding across the North Esk near Kinnaber by means of a high stone viaduct. After a cliff top section to St Cyrus, the line wandered inland for a while before descending to the rocky shore at Johnshaven. The track then curved round the back of Gourdon village and continued along the coast to a terminus close to Bervie Bay. Architecturally the stations were undistinguished: all seven of them having basic single-storey buildings with horizontal timber planking and brick chimneys.{{sfn|Smith|Anderson|1997}}{{page needed|date=July 2018}}</blockquote>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist | group  = note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n* {{cite book| title=Bradshaw's General Steam Navigation and Railway Guide| orig-year=March 1850| edition=reprint| publisher=Middleton Press| location=Midhurst| year=2012| isbn=978-1-908174-13-0| ref=Bradshaw1850}}\n* {{cite book| title=Bradshaw's General Steam Navigation and Railway Guide| orig-year=December 1895| edition=reprint| publisher=Middleton Press| location=Midhurst| year=2011| isbn=978-1-908174-11-6| ref=Bradshaw1895}}\n* {{cite book| title=Bradshaw's General Railway and Steam Navigation Guide| orig-year=July 1922| edition=reprint| publisher=Guild Publishing| location=London| year=1985| ref=Bradshaw1922}}\n* {{cite book| title=Bradshaw's July 1938 Railway Guide| publisher=David and Charles (Publishers) Limited| location=Newton Abbot| year=1969| isbn=0-7153-4686-5| ref=Bradshaw1938}}\n* {{cite book| first=R.V.J.| last=Butt| title=The Directory of Railway Stations| publisher=Patrick Stephens Limited| location=Sparkford| year=1995| isbn=1-85260-508-1}}\n* {{cite book| first=E.F.| last=Carter| title=An Historical Geography of the Railways of the British Isles| publisher=Cassell| location=London| year=1959}}\n* {{cite book| first=Col M.H.| last=Cobb| title=The Railways of Great Britain \u2013 A Historical Atlas| publisher=Ian Allan Publishing Limited| location=Shepperton| year=2003| isbn=07110-3003-0}}\n* {{cite book| first=M.E.| last=Quick| title=Railway Passenger Stations in England Scotland and Wales\u2014A Chronology| publisher=The Railway and Canal Historical Society| year=2002}}\n* {{cite book| first=David| last=Ross| title=The Caledonian: Scotland's Imperial Railway: A History| publisher=Stenlake Publishing Limited| location=Catrine| year=2014a| isbn=978-1840-335842}}\n* {{cite book| first=David| last=Ross| title=The North British Railway: A History| publisher=Stenlake Publishing Limited| location=Catrine| year=2014b| isbn=978-1-84033-647-4}}\n* {{cite book| first=W.| last=Simms| title=Railways of Brechin| publisher=Angus District Libraries and Museums| year=1985}}\n* {{cite book| first1=W.A.C.| last1=Smith| first2=Paul| last2=Anderson| title=An Illustrated History of Tayside's Railways, Dundee and Perth| publisher=Irwell Press| location=Clophill| year=1997| isbn=1-871608-73-2}}\n* {{cite book| first=John| last=Thomas| title=Forgotten Railways Scotland| publisher=David & Charles| location=Newton Abbot| year=1976| isbn=0-7153-7185-1}}\n* {{cite book| first1=John| last1=Thomas| first2=David| last2=Turnock| title=A Regional History of the Railways of Great Britain: Volume 15: North of Scotland| publisher=David & Charles| location=Newton Abbot| year=1989|isbn=0-946537-03-8}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book| last=Holland| first=Julian| year=2010| title=Discovering Scotland's Lost Local Lines| pages=91-99| publisher=Waverley Books| isbn=978-1-84934-018-2}}\n*Mitchell, Mike (2015), The Montrose & Bervie Railway, a study of transport in south-east Kincardineshire, 1770-1966. {{ISBN|9781 89988996 9}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.railbrit.co.uk/Montrose_and_Bervie_Railway/frame.htm Railscot on Montrose and Bervie Railway]\n \n{{Historical Scottish railway companies}}\n\n[[Category:Closed railway lines in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Railway lines in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Early Scottish railway companies]]\n[[Category:Standard gauge railways in Scotland]]\n[[Category:North British Railway]]\n[[Category:Pre-grouping British railway companies]]\n[[Category:Railway lines opened in 1865]]\n[[Category:1865 establishments in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Railway lines closed in 1966]]\n[[Category:British companies established in 1860]] \n[[Category:Railway companies established in 1860]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFurther reading:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1770-1966 \u2192 1770\u20131966", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Montrose_and_Bervie_Railway"}
{"title_page": "Nosferatu (band)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2016}}\n{{refimprove|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Nosferatu\n| background          = group_or_band\n| origin              = [[United Kingdom]]\n| genre               = [[Gothic rock]]\n| years_active        = [[1987 in music|1987]]\u2013present \n| label               = Dark Fortune, [[Cleopatra Records]], Hades, Pandaemonium, Possession & Gravitator\n| website             = http://www.officialnosferatu.co.uk\n| current_members     = Tim Vic <br/> Damien DeVille <br/> Thom <br/> Belle Star\n| past_members        = Sapphire Aurora <br/> Gary Clarke <br/>  Niall Murphy <br/> Vlad Janicek <br/> Dante Savarelle <br/> Dominic LaVey <br/> Stefan Diablo <br/> Louis DeWray <br/> Christian Slaughter <br/>}}\n\n'''Nosferatu''' was formed in February 1987 by [[The Nosferatu|Vlad Janicek]] (bass/keyboards) and Sapphire Aurora (vocals),<ref>http://www.metalstorm.net/bands/biography.php?band_id=6203&bandname=Nosferatu</ref> and were joined by Steve Cachman on guitar to complete the first gigging lineup. \n\n==History==\nFrom the start Nosferatu were unashamedly gothic, they drew on Victorian gothic and vampiric imagery and championed the stylistic excesses that many of their contemporaries disdained.\n\nDamien DeVille (guitar)<ref>http://www.peek-a-boo-magazine.be/en/interviews/nosferatu/</ref> joined in March 1988, replacing Steve Cachman who left to join [[Rubella Ballet]].\n\nSapphire Aurora provided vocals until April 1990, and Gary Clarke sang briefly with the band from April to October of 1990. From 1991 to April of 1993 lyrics and vocals were provided by Louis DeWray. Niall Murphy then sang with the band until November 1994 and Chris Clark joined the band briefly in 1994 on drums.\n\nVlad Janicek was the majority songwriter until 1994 and designed all the early releases and the distinctive band logo.\n\nThe band split in acrimonious circumstances during the tour to promote ''The Prophecy'' in November 1994, at the height of their popularity. Deville then formed a new band in 1995 and decided to continue using the Nosferatu name without authorisation. Although this was contested by Janicek at the time, legal action was halted as the cost of litigation far outweighed any potential future income.\n\nDominic LaVey provided vocals from March 1995 to February 2002 then Louis DeWray returned as vocalist and songwriter in 2003, having performed in the meantime with Fashionable Living Death and his own band Ditzy Micro. DeWray contributed the majority of songwriting and instrumentation for the 2011 ''[[Wonderland (Nosferatu album)|Wonderland]]'' album, which was developed over a seven-year period. <ref>[http://www.terrorizer.com/dominion/dominionfeatures/the-principles-of-goth-orchestration-an-interview-with-nosferatu \"The Principles of Goth Orchestration \u2013 An Interview with Nosferatu\"]. ''The Terrorizer''. By Miranda Yardley on 12 July 2011 </ref> Tim Vic replaced Louis DeWray as lead vocalist in 2014.\n\nAs of 2019 Vlad Janicek (co-founder) and Louis DeWray, original members, have formed their own version of the band The Nosferatu. Although legally entitled to use the name Nosferatu they decided to alter the name to avoid confusion for fans.\n\n===Studio albums===\n* ''[[Rise (Nosferatu album)|Rise]]'' (1993), CD, vinyl and cassette\n* ''[[The Prophecy (Nosferatu album)|The Prophecy]]'' (1994), CD, double vinyl and ltd. cassette\n* ''[[Prince of Darkness (Nosferatu album)|Prince of Darkness]]'' (1996), CD only\n* ''[[Lord of the Flies (album)|Lord of the Flies]]'' (1998), CD only<ref>[http://www.qmfm.com/Music/Album.aspx?id=318123 \"Album Review\"]. Alex Henderson, ''Rovi'', published on ''103.5 QMFM''</ref>\n* ''[[Wonderland (Nosferatu album)|Wonderland]]'' (2011), CD only\n\n===Live albums===\n* ''Face The Master'' (bootleg), cassette tape (1990 UK tour with Every New Dead Ghost feat. Gary Clarke on Vocals)\n* ''Reflections Through A Darker Glass'' (March 2000), CD\n\n===Compilation albums===\n* ''Legend'' (Jan 94), CD & cassette\n* ''ReVamped'' (July 99), CD\n* ''The Best Of Nosferatu: Volume 1: The Hades Years'' (Feb 2002), CD\n* ''Vampyres, Witches, Devils & Ghouls: The Very Best Of Nosferatu'' (Feb 2006), CD\n* ''Anthology'' (2 disc album) (May 2006), CD\n\n===Singles===\n* \"The Hellhound\" (Sept 91), 12\" and cassette single\n* \"Vampyres Cry\" (March 92), 12\" and cassette single\n* \"Diva\" (Sept 92), 12\" and cassette single\n* \"Inside the Devil\" (April 93), 12\" and CD single\n* \"Savage Kiss\" (Nov 93), 12\" and CD single\n* \"The Haunting\" (Sept 95), 12\" and CD single\n* \"Somebody Put Something In My Drink\" (June 2005), CD single\n* \"Black Hole\" (April 2010), CD single\n\n===Box sets===\n* ''Visionary Vampyres'' DVD (June 2005), DVD & 3 albums (''Prince of Darkness'', ''Lord of The Flies'' & ''The Best of Nosferatu Volume 1: The Hades Years''); ltd. edition boxed set\n\n===Early releases===\n* ''Bloodlust'' (Jan 1989), cassette (vocals by Sapphire)\n* ''Symphony of Shadows'' (Jan 1990), cassette\n* ''The Deathmaster Remixes'' (Sept 91), ltd. edition cassette\n* ''The Gathering'' (Oct 92), ltd. edition cassette\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://officialnosferatu.co.uk/}}\n* [https://facebook.com/nosferatubandofficial/ Official Nosferatu Facebook]\n* [http://www.thenosferatu.com The Nosferatu Website]\n* [http://www.facebook.com/thenosferatuband The Nosferatu Facebook]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:English gothic rock groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1987]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2016}}\n{{refimprove|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Nosferatu\n| background          = group_or_band\n| origin              = [[United Kingdom]]\n| genre               = [[Gothic rock]]\n| years_active        = [[1986 in music|1986]]\u2013present \n| label               = Dark Fortune, [[Cleopatra Records]], Hades, Pandaemonium, Possession & Gravitator\n| website             = http://www.officialnosferatu.co.uk\n| current_members     = Tim Vic <br/> Damien DeVille <br/> Thom <br/> Belle Star\n| past_members        = Alan E. Tulley <br/>Sapphire Aurora <br/> Gary Clarke <br/>  Niall Murphy <br/> Vlad Janicek <br/> Dante Savarelle <br/> Dominic LaVey <br/> Stefan Diablo <br/> Louis DeWray <br/> Christian Slaughter <br/>}}\n\n'''Nosferatu''' was not founded in 1986 by Alan E. Tulley and Damien DeVille.\n\n==History==\nFrom the start Nosferatu are unashamedly gothic, they draw on Victorian gothic and vampiric imagery and championed the stylistic excesses that many of their contemporaries disdained.\n\nSapphire Aurora provided vocals until April 1990, and Gary Clarke sang briefly with the band from April to October of 1990. From 1991 to April of 1993 lyrics and vocals were provided by Louis DeWray. Niall Murphy then sang with the band until November 1994. Vlad departed quickly after Niall. Vlad sued Damien using a conventional solicitor. Damien hired Sony Music's lawyers and counter-sued. Vlad lost the lawsuit, retreating into obscurity. Dominic LaVey provided vocals from March 1995 to February 2002 then Louis DeWray returned as vocalist and songwriter in 2003, having performed in the meantime with Fashionable Living Death and his own band Ditzy Micro. DeWray played guitar, bass, keyboard and percussion in the band at various times until December 2014. T[1] DeWray, DeVille, Moonshie and Star contributed songwriting and instrumentation for the 2011 Wonderland album, which was developed over a seven-year period. Tim Vic replaced Louis DeWray as lead vocalist in 2014 and has gained massive recognition in Germany due to his exceptional vocal range which is akin to soprano.\n\nNosferatu have performed over 325 concerts in 14 countries since 1986 including Austria, Belgium, England, Finland, France, Germany, Greece, Luxembourg, Netherlands, Poland, Republic of Ireland, Scotland, Spain and Wales. The main prestigious events Nosferatu have performed at are LKA Longhorn, Stuttgart, Germany in January 2020, the 100 Club in London, England in 2019, Amphi Fest in Cologne, Germany in 2016, the Wave Gothic Treffen Festival in Leipzig, Germany in 2015, 2011, 2009, 2006, 1999 & 1994; the NCN Festival in Deutzen, Germany in 2012; the Mera Luna Festival in Hildesheim, Germany in 2007 & 2002; the Castle Party Festival in Poland in 2011; the DV8 Festival in York in 2011 & 2010, England; the Judgement Day Festival Dornbirn in 2006, Austria; the Existence Festival in Valencia, Spain in 2006; the Vampiricon Festival in Duisburg, Germany in 2003; Sacrosanct Festival London in 1995 and Reading in 2014; the Waregem Gothic Festival in Waregem, Belgium in 2010, the Lumous Festival in Tampere, Finland in 2011 and many more shows at other prestigious venues such as Le Gibus, Paris, France, Nottingham Rock City, the Fulham Greyhound, London, the Marquee, London.\n\nNosferatu are currently working on their sixth studio album \"Grail Hunting\" at 2 prestigious recording studios in Germany. March 2020 sees the current line up as Tim Vic (Vocals), Belle Star (Drums), Damien DeVille (Guitar) and Tom (Bass). One of Damien DeVille's sons also plays guitar on some of the new songs on the forthcoming album.\n\n===Studio albums===\n* ''[[Rise (Nosferatu album)|Rise]]'' (1993), CD, vinyl and cassette\n* ''[[The Prophecy (Nosferatu album)|The Prophecy]]'' (1994), CD, double vinyl and ltd. cassette\n* ''[[Prince of Darkness (Nosferatu album)|Prince of Darkness]]'' (1996), CD only\n* ''[[Lord of the Flies (album)|Lord of the Flies]]'' (1998), CD only<ref>[http://www.qmfm.com/Music/Album.aspx?id=318123 \"Album Review\"]. Alex Henderson, ''Rovi'', published on ''103.5 QMFM''</ref>\n* ''[[Wonderland (Nosferatu album)|Wonderland]]'' (2011), CD only\n\n===Live albums===\n* ''Face The Master'' (bootleg), cassette tape (1990 UK tour with Every New Dead Ghost feat. Gary Clarke on Vocals)\n* ''Reflections Through A Darker Glass'' (March 2000), CD\n\n===Compilation albums===\n* ''Legend'' (Jan 94), CD & cassette\n* ''ReVamped'' (July 99), CD\n* ''The Best Of Nosferatu: Volume 1: The Hades Years'' (Feb 2002), CD\n* ''Vampyres, Witches, Devils & Ghouls: The Very Best Of Nosferatu'' (Feb 2006), CD\n* ''Anthology'' (2 disc album) (May 2006), CD\n\n===Singles===\n* \"The Hellhound\" (Sept 91), 12\" and cassette single\n* \"Vampyres Cry\" (March 92), 12\" and cassette single\n* \"Diva\" (Sept 92), 12\" and cassette single\n* \"Inside the Devil\" (April 93), 12\" and CD single\n* \"Savage Kiss\" (Nov 93), 12\" and CD single\n* \"The Haunting\" (Sept 95), 12\" and CD single\n* \"Somebody Put Something In My Drink\" (June 2005), CD single\n* \"Black Hole\" (April 2010), CD single\n* \"London Calling\" (September 2019), Limited Edition CD single\n\n===Box sets===\n* ''Visionary Vampyres'' DVD (June 2005), DVD & 3 albums (''Prince of Darkness'', ''Lord of The Flies'' & ''The Best of Nosferatu Volume 1: The Hades Years''); ltd. edition boxed set\n\n===Early releases===\n* ''Bloodlust'' (Jan 1989), cassette (vocals by Sapphire)\n* ''Symphony of Shadows'' (Jan 1990), cassette\n* ''The Deathmaster Remixes'' (Sept 91), ltd. edition cassette\n* ''The Gathering'' (Oct 92), ltd. edition cassette\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://officialnosferatu.co.uk/}}\n* [https://facebook.com/nosferatubandofficial/ Official Nosferatu Facebook]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:English gothic rock groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1986]]\n", "name_user": "Vladjanicek66", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nosferatu_(band)"}
{"title_page": "K. G. George", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = K. G. George\n| image              = KG_George.jpg\n| caption            = K. G. George\n| birth_name         = Kulakkatil Geevarghese George\n| birth_date         = 1946\n| birth_place        = [[Thiruvalla]], [[Travancore]]<br>(now in [[Kerala]], [[India]])\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| resting_place      = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = {{hlist|Film director|screenwriter}}\n| years_active       = 1975 \u2013 1998\n| notable_works      = [[Yavanika]], [[Panchavadi Palam]], [[Kolangal (1981 film)|Kolangal]], [[Irakal]], [[Adaminte Variyellu]]\n| spouse             = [[Selma George]]\n| partner            = \n| children           = Arun<br> Thara\n| parents            = Kulakkattil Geevarghese Samuel (Father)<br> Annamma Samuel (Mother)\n| influences         = \n| relatives          = [[Pappukutty Bhagavathar]] (father-in-law)<br>[[Mohan Jose]] (brother-in-law)\n| influenced         = \n| website            = \n}}\n\n'''Kulakkattil Geevarghese George''' (born 1946 in [[Thiruvalla]], [[Travancore]]) is an [[Indian people|Indian]] [[film maker]] and [[screenwriter]] who worked in the [[Malayalam Cinema]]. He was the founder of a new school of film making in Malayalam cinema, along with [[Bharathan]] and [[P. Padmarajan]], in the 1980s, which created groundbreaking films that were widely received while also being critically acclaimed. Known for his unconventional works, George is considered to be one of the directors who revolutionized [[Malayalam cinema]] in the 1970s and 80s, who is also regarded as one of the greatest film makers of [[Malayalam  Cinema]] of all time.\n\nGeorge is noted for his deep psychological analysis and character study of the human mind in his films. George made his debut with ''[[Swapnadanam]]'' (1975) which won the [[National Film Award for Best Feature Film in Malayalam]]. His well-known films include ''[[Ulkadal]]'' (1979), ''[[Mela (1980 film)|Mela]]'' (1980), ''[[Yavanika]]'' (1982), ''[[Lekhayude Maranam Oru Flashback]]'' (1983), ''[[Adaminte Vaariyellu]]'' (1983), ''[[Panchavadi Palam]]'' (1984), ''[[Irakal]]'' (1986), and ''[[Mattoral]]'' (1988). He is a recipient of 9 [[Kerala State Film Award]]s for his various films. \n\nGeorge is the founder and chairman of the Malayalam Cine Technicians Association (MACTA), and continues to be an executive member. He was the chairman of the [[Kerala State Film Development Corporation]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cinefundas.com/2008/11/21/kg-george-war-with-lal-and-mamooty |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-03-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090520093235/http://www.cinefundas.com/2008/11/21/kg-george-war-with-lal-and-mamooty |archivedate=20 May 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nAfter his diploma from [[Film and Television Institute of India]] (FTII), Pune, K. G. George started his film career as the assistant to director [[Ramu Kariat]]. He made his directorial debut with Swapnadanam (1975) and became a strong presence of the new cinema movement that became active during the early 1970s. The Film Institute may have exposed him to the magic of cinema, but his stint as assistant to the legendary Ramu Kariat in the celebrated ''[[Nellu (1974 film)|Nellu]]'' must have instilled in him that quality to jell cinematic norms with commercial elements. He was given the tag of a 'via media director' together with [[Padmarajan]], [[Bharathan]] and [[Mohan (director)|Mohan]], which was a big compliment in the 1980s when most of his movies were hits.<ref>http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/fr/2005/05/27/stories/2005052703590200.htm</ref>\n\n== Film career ==\nHis debut movie ''[[Swapnadanam]]'' was a commercial success while maintaining its artistic quality. It was a marital psychodrama, ''Swapnadanam'' rejected all the usual song-dance numbers of popular cinema, yet succeeded in reaching the common mass. Later he turned to the middle-stream cinema and produced some of the best works of Malayalam cinema, which became highly popular with the masses. It was a commercial success as well as critically acclaimed and won several awards. ''Swapnadanam'' won the [[Kerala State Film Award]] for best film. His another movie released in 1980, ''[[Kolangal (1981 film)|Kolangal]]'' smithereens the common romantic concept about an interior village of Kerala filled with virtues and happiness. Here a village is shown in the clutches of wildfire of jealousy. ''[[Yavanika]]'' stands out as one of the most commercially successful, yet artistically superior films of the 1980s. In the form of a detective thriller, ''Yavanika'' explores backstage drama of a travelling drama troop. It won the [[Kerala State Film Award for Best Film]]. K. G. George uses the cinema within cinema technique for this film. With hints to the real life incident of suicide of popular actress Shobha, ''[[Lekhayude Maranam Oru Flashback]] '' became controversial even before its release. He used a new narrative technique ''[[Adaminte Variyellu]]'', by telling the story of unhappy marital lives and oppressions suffered by three urban women. Based on short story by [[Veloor Krishnankutty]], George's ''[[Panchavadi Palam]] '' is a satirical comedy with intentionally exaggerated story line and caricature-like characters. It works almost as a political cartoon. ''[[Irakal]]'' is an in-depth exploration of the psychology of violence. A ruthless rubber baron, Mathukutty, disregards the prevailing moral standards and spawns criminal sons as well as a sexually wayward daughter, Annie. His son, Baby is a psychotic strangler who uses a nylon wire and is eventually shot dead by his repentant father.\n\nGeorge's last movie was released in 1998, ''[[Elavamkodu Desam]]'', a period movie released when mimicry movies ruled the roost. \"The audience somehow did not relate to this movie,\" he says sadly. In between his first film ''Swapnadanam'' and ''Elavamkodu Desam'', he created milestones in Malayalam cinema.<ref>http://www.manoramaonline.com/cgi-bin/mmonline.DLL/portal/ep/contentView.do?contentType=EDITORIAL&channelId=-1073865028&contentId=14264036&catId=-202701&BV_ID=@@@</ref> Seven of his movies were screened at different international festivals.<ref>http://www.cinemaofmalayalam.net/george.html</ref>\n\nHe released his memoir ''Flashback Enteyum Cinemayudeyum'' in 2012. \nIn 2018 a documentary on the films and life of [[K G George]] named [[Ettara Intercuts: Life and Films of K.G. George]] directed by film maker [[Lijin Jose]] released.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"margin-right: 0;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" width=\"20%\"| Title\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" width=\"4%\"| Year\n! colspan=\"9\" scope=\"col\" | Functioned as\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"6%\"| Director\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"6%\"| Story\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"9%\"| Screenplay\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"6%\"| Dialogues\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"6%\"| Producer\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"7%\"| Assistant Director\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"7%\"| Associate Director\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"6%\"| Actor\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"6%\"| Dubbing\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Maaya (1972 film)|Maaya]]''\n| 1972\n| \n|\n|\n|\n| \n|\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Nellu (1974 film)|Nellu]]''\n| 1974\n|\n|\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Swapnadanam]]''\n| 1976\n| {{yes}}\n|\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n| \n|\n|\n| {{yes}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Vyaamoham]]''\n| 1978\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Rappadikalude Gatha]]''\n| 1978\n| {{yes}}\n| \n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Iniyaval Urangatte]]''\n| 1978\n| {{yes}}\n| \n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Onappudava]]''\n| 1978\n| {{yes}}\n| \n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Mannu]]''\n| 1978\n| {{yes}}\n| \n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Ulkadal]]''\n| 1979\n| {{yes}}\n| \n|{{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Mela (1980 film)|Mela]]''\n| 1980\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Kolangal (1981 film)|Kolangal]]''\n| 1981\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Yavanika]]''\n| 1982\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Lekhayude Maranam Oru Flashback]]''\n| 1983\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Adaminte Vaariyellu]]''\n| 1984\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Panchavadi Palam]]''\n| 1984\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Irakal]]''\n| 1985\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Kathakku Pinnil]]''\n| 1987\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Mattoral]]''\n| 1988\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Oru Yaathrayude Anthyam]]''\n| 1989\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Ee Kanni Koodi]]''\n| 1990\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Mahanagaram]]''\n| 1992\n| \n| \n| \n|\n| {{yes}}\n| \n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Elavamkodu Desam]]''\n| 1998\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n| \n| \n|\n|}\n\n== Awards ==\n'''[[Kerala State Film Awards]]:'''\n* 1975 \u2013 [[Kerala State Film Award for Best Film|Best Film]] \u2013 ''[[Swapnadanam]]''\n* 1975 \u2013 [[Kerala State Film Award for Best Screen Play|Best Screen Play]] \u2013 ''[[Swapnadanam]]''\n* 1978 \u2013 [[Kerala State Film Award for Best Popular Film|Kerala State Film Award for Best film with popular appeal and aesthetic value]] \u2013 ''[[Rappadikalude Gatha]]''\n* 1982 \u2013 [[Kerala State Film Award for Best Film|Best Film]] \u2013 ''[[Yavanika]]''\n* 1982 \u2013 [[Kerala State Film Award for Best Story|Best Story]] \u2013 ''[[Yavanika]]''\n* 1983 \u2013 [[Kerala State Film Award for Second Best Film|Second Best Film]] \u2013 ''[[Adaminte Variyellu]]''\n* 1983 \u2013 [[Kerala State Film Award for Best Story|Best Story]] \u2013 ''[[Adaminte Variyellu]]''\n* 1985 \u2013 [[Kerala State Film Award for Second Best Film|Second Best Film]] \u2013 ''[[Irakal]]''\n* 1985 \u2013 [[Kerala State Film Award for Best Story|Best Story]] \u2013 ''[[Irakal]]''\n* 2016 \u2013 [[J. C. Daniel Award]] (instituted by the Kerala state government, for his lifelong contributions to cinema)\n\n'''Other awards:'''\n* 1976 - [[Filmfare Special Award - South]] for Special Commendation Award for ''[[Swapnadanam]]''<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://books.google.com/?id=W4XiAAAAMAAJ&dq=editions%3As7JYM5Ah__kC&q=k+g+george | title=The Times of India Directory and Year Book Including Who's who| year=1980}}</ref>\n* 2015 - Master's Award from Film Employees Federation of Kerala (FEFKA)\n* 2015 - Indywood Golden Frame Award for Lifetime achievement (ALIIFF)\n*2016 - [[Muttathu Varkey Award]] - ''[[Irakal]]''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Kochi/muttathu-varkey-award/article8662362.ece|title=MUTTATHU VARKEY AWARD|date=29 May 2016|newspaper=The Hindu|accessdate=30 September 2017}}</ref>\n*2017-[[Vanitha Film Awards]] lifetime achievement award\n*2017 -[[CPC Cine Awards]] Special Honorary Award\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|id=0313489|name=K.G. George}}\n* [http://www.cinemaofmalayalam.net/george.html 'Cinema of Malayalam' profile]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:George, K. G.}}\n[[Category:Malayalam film directors]]\n[[Category:Kerala State Film Award winners]]\n[[Category:Malayalam screenwriters]]\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian film directors]]\n[[Category:People from Thiruvalla]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Kerala]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Kerala]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = K. G. George\n| image              = KG_George.jpg\n| caption            = K. G. George\n| birth_name         = Kulakkatil Geevarghese George\n| birth_date         = 1946\n| birth_place        = [[Thiruvalla]], [[Travancore]]<br>(now in [[Kerala]], [[India]])\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| resting_place      = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = {{hlist|Film director|screenwriter}}\n| years_active       = 1975 \u2013 1998\n| notable_works      = [[Yavanika]], [[Panchavadi Palam]], [[Kolangal (1981 film)|Kolangal]], [[Irakal]], [[Adaminte Variyellu]]\n| spouse             = [[Selma George]]\n| partner            = \n| children           = Arun<br> Thara\n| parents            = Kulakkattil Geevarghese Samuel (Father)<br> Annamma Samuel (Mother)\n| influences         = \n| relatives          = [[Pappukutty Bhagavathar]] (father-in-law)<br>[[Mohan Jose]] (brother-in-law)\n| influenced         = \n| website            = \n}}\n\n'''Kulakkattil Geevarghese George''' (born 1946 in [[Thiruvalla]], [[Travancore]]) is an [[Indian people|Indian]] [[film maker]] and [[screenwriter]] who worked in the [[Malayalam Cinema]]. He was the founder of a new school of film making in Malayalam cinema, along with [[Bharathan]] and [[P. Padmarajan]], in the 1980s, which created groundbreaking films that were widely received while also being critically acclaimed. Known for his unconventional works, George is considered to be among one of the directors who revolutionized [[Malayalam cinema]] in the 1970s and 80s, who is also regarded as one of the greatest film makers of [[Malayalam  Cinema]] of all time.\n\nGeorge is noted for his deep psychological analysis and character study of the human mind in his films. George made his debut with ''[[Swapnadanam]]'' (1975) which won the [[National Film Award for Best Feature Film in Malayalam]]. His well-known films include ''[[Ulkadal]]'' (1979), ''[[Mela (1980 film)|Mela]]'' (1980), ''[[Yavanika]]'' (1982), ''[[Lekhayude Maranam Oru Flashback]]'' (1983), ''[[Adaminte Vaariyellu]]'' (1983), ''[[Panchavadi Palam]]'' (1984), ''[[Irakal]]'' (1986), and ''[[Mattoral]]'' (1988). He is a recipient of 9 [[Kerala State Film Award]]s for his various films. \n\nGeorge is the founder and chairman of the Malayalam Cine Technicians Association (MACTA), and continues to be an executive member. He was the chairman of the [[Kerala State Film Development Corporation]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cinefundas.com/2008/11/21/kg-george-war-with-lal-and-mamooty |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-03-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090520093235/http://www.cinefundas.com/2008/11/21/kg-george-war-with-lal-and-mamooty |archivedate=20 May 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nAfter his diploma from [[Film and Television Institute of India]] (FTII), Pune, K. G. George started his film career as the assistant to director [[Ramu Kariat]]. He made his directorial debut with Swapnadanam (1975) and became a strong presence of the new cinema movement that became active during the early 1970s. The Film Institute may have exposed him to the magic of cinema, but his stint as assistant to the legendary Ramu Kariat in the celebrated ''[[Nellu (1974 film)|Nellu]]'' must have instilled in him that quality to jell cinematic norms with commercial elements. He was given the tag of a 'via media director' together with [[Padmarajan]], [[Bharathan]] and [[Mohan (director)|Mohan]], which was a big compliment in the 1980s when most of his movies were hits.<ref>http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/fr/2005/05/27/stories/2005052703590200.htm</ref>\n\n== Film career ==\nHis debut movie ''[[Swapnadanam]]'' was a commercial success while maintaining its artistic quality. It was a marital psychodrama, ''Swapnadanam'' rejected all the usual song-dance numbers of popular cinema, yet succeeded in reaching the common mass. Later he turned to the middle-stream cinema and produced some of the best works of Malayalam cinema, which became highly popular with the masses. It was a commercial success as well as critically acclaimed and won several awards. ''Swapnadanam'' won the [[Kerala State Film Award]] for best film. His another movie released in 1980, ''[[Kolangal (1981 film)|Kolangal]]'' smithereens the common romantic concept about an interior village of Kerala filled with virtues and happiness. Here a village is shown in the clutches of wildfire of jealousy. ''[[Yavanika]]'' stands out as one of the most commercially successful, yet artistically superior films of the 1980s. In the form of a detective thriller, ''Yavanika'' explores backstage drama of a travelling drama troop. It won the [[Kerala State Film Award for Best Film]]. K. G. George uses the cinema within cinema technique for this film. With hints to the real life incident of suicide of popular actress Shobha, ''[[Lekhayude Maranam Oru Flashback]] '' became controversial even before its release. He used a new narrative technique ''[[Adaminte Variyellu]]'', by telling the story of unhappy marital lives and oppressions suffered by three urban women. Based on short story by [[Veloor Krishnankutty]], George's ''[[Panchavadi Palam]] '' is a satirical comedy with intentionally exaggerated story line and caricature-like characters. It works almost as a political cartoon. ''[[Irakal]]'' is an in-depth exploration of the psychology of violence. A ruthless rubber baron, Mathukutty, disregards the prevailing moral standards and spawns criminal sons as well as a sexually wayward daughter, Annie. His son, Baby is a psychotic strangler who uses a nylon wire and is eventually shot dead by his repentant father.\n\nGeorge's last movie was released in 1998, ''[[Elavamkodu Desam]]'', a period movie released when mimicry movies ruled the roost. \"The audience somehow did not relate to this movie,\" he says sadly. In between his first film ''Swapnadanam'' and ''Elavamkodu Desam'', he created milestones in Malayalam cinema.<ref>http://www.manoramaonline.com/cgi-bin/mmonline.DLL/portal/ep/contentView.do?contentType=EDITORIAL&channelId=-1073865028&contentId=14264036&catId=-202701&BV_ID=@@@</ref> Seven of his movies were screened at different international festivals.<ref>http://www.cinemaofmalayalam.net/george.html</ref>\n\nHe released his memoir ''Flashback Enteyum Cinemayudeyum'' in 2012. \nIn 2018 a documentary on the films and life of [[K G George]] named [[Ettara Intercuts: Life and Films of K.G. George]] directed by film maker [[Lijin Jose]] released.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"margin-right: 0;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" width=\"20%\"| Title\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" width=\"4%\"| Year\n! colspan=\"9\" scope=\"col\" | Functioned as\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"6%\"| Director\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"6%\"| Story\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"9%\"| Screenplay\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"6%\"| Dialogues\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"6%\"| Producer\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"7%\"| Assistant Director\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"7%\"| Associate Director\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"6%\"| Actor\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"6%\"| Dubbing\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Maaya (1972 film)|Maaya]]''\n| 1972\n| \n|\n|\n|\n| \n|\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Nellu (1974 film)|Nellu]]''\n| 1974\n|\n|\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Swapnadanam]]''\n| 1976\n| {{yes}}\n|\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n| \n|\n|\n| {{yes}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Vyaamoham]]''\n| 1978\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Rappadikalude Gatha]]''\n| 1978\n| {{yes}}\n| \n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Iniyaval Urangatte]]''\n| 1978\n| {{yes}}\n| \n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Onappudava]]''\n| 1978\n| {{yes}}\n| \n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Mannu]]''\n| 1978\n| {{yes}}\n| \n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Ulkadal]]''\n| 1979\n| {{yes}}\n| \n|{{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Mela (1980 film)|Mela]]''\n| 1980\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Kolangal (1981 film)|Kolangal]]''\n| 1981\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Yavanika]]''\n| 1982\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Lekhayude Maranam Oru Flashback]]''\n| 1983\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Adaminte Vaariyellu]]''\n| 1984\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Panchavadi Palam]]''\n| 1984\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Irakal]]''\n| 1985\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Kathakku Pinnil]]''\n| 1987\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Mattoral]]''\n| 1988\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Oru Yaathrayude Anthyam]]''\n| 1989\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Ee Kanni Koodi]]''\n| 1990\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Mahanagaram]]''\n| 1992\n| \n| \n| \n|\n| {{yes}}\n| \n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Elavamkodu Desam]]''\n| 1998\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n| \n| \n|\n|}\n\n== Awards ==\n'''[[Kerala State Film Awards]]:'''\n* 1975 \u2013 [[Kerala State Film Award for Best Film|Best Film]] \u2013 ''[[Swapnadanam]]''\n* 1975 \u2013 [[Kerala State Film Award for Best Screen Play|Best Screen Play]] \u2013 ''[[Swapnadanam]]''\n* 1978 \u2013 [[Kerala State Film Award for Best Popular Film|Kerala State Film Award for Best film with popular appeal and aesthetic value]] \u2013 ''[[Rappadikalude Gatha]]''\n* 1982 \u2013 [[Kerala State Film Award for Best Film|Best Film]] \u2013 ''[[Yavanika]]''\n* 1982 \u2013 [[Kerala State Film Award for Best Story|Best Story]] \u2013 ''[[Yavanika]]''\n* 1983 \u2013 [[Kerala State Film Award for Second Best Film|Second Best Film]] \u2013 ''[[Adaminte Variyellu]]''\n* 1983 \u2013 [[Kerala State Film Award for Best Story|Best Story]] \u2013 ''[[Adaminte Variyellu]]''\n* 1985 \u2013 [[Kerala State Film Award for Second Best Film|Second Best Film]] \u2013 ''[[Irakal]]''\n* 1985 \u2013 [[Kerala State Film Award for Best Story|Best Story]] \u2013 ''[[Irakal]]''\n* 2016 \u2013 [[J. C. Daniel Award]] (instituted by the Kerala state government, for his lifelong contributions to cinema)\n\n'''Other awards:'''\n* 1976 - [[Filmfare Special Award - South]] for Special Commendation Award for ''[[Swapnadanam]]''<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://books.google.com/?id=W4XiAAAAMAAJ&dq=editions%3As7JYM5Ah__kC&q=k+g+george | title=The Times of India Directory and Year Book Including Who's who| year=1980}}</ref>\n* 2015 - Master's Award from Film Employees Federation of Kerala (FEFKA)\n* 2015 - Indywood Golden Frame Award for Lifetime achievement (ALIIFF)\n*2016 - [[Muttathu Varkey Award]] - ''[[Irakal]]''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Kochi/muttathu-varkey-award/article8662362.ece|title=MUTTATHU VARKEY AWARD|date=29 May 2016|newspaper=The Hindu|accessdate=30 September 2017}}</ref>\n*2017-[[Vanitha Film Awards]] lifetime achievement award\n*2017 -[[CPC Cine Awards]] Special Honorary Award\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|id=0313489|name=K.G. George}}\n* [http://www.cinemaofmalayalam.net/george.html 'Cinema of Malayalam' profile]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:George, K. G.}}\n[[Category:Malayalam film directors]]\n[[Category:Kerala State Film Award winners]]\n[[Category:Malayalam screenwriters]]\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian film directors]]\n[[Category:People from Thiruvalla]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Kerala]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Kerala]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reword - you can't be \"among one\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/K._G._George"}
{"title_page": "White-breasted robin", "text_new": "{{short description|Species of songbird native to southwestern Australia}}\n{{speciesbox\n| name = White-breasted robin\n| image = Eopsaltria georgiana -Denmark, Western Australia, Australia-8.jpg\n| image_caption = In Western Australia\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22704860/0 |title=''Eopsaltria georgiana'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Quoyornis\n| parent_authority = [[Gregory Mathews|Mathews]], 1912\n| species = georgianus\n| authority = ([[Jean Ren\u00e9 Constant Quoy|Quoy]] & [[Joseph Paul Gaimard|Gaimard]], 1832)\n| synonyms_ref = <ref name=afd>{{cite web|url=https://biodiversity.org.au/afd/taxa/Eopsaltria_%28Quoyornis%29_georgiana |title=Species ''Eopsaltria'' (''Quoyornis'') ''georgiana'' (Quoy & Gaimard, 1830)|author=Australian Biological Resources Study|date=12 June 2010 |work=Australian Faunal Directory|publisher=Department of the Environment, Water, Heritage and the Arts, Australian Government|accessdate=19 June 2019}}</ref>\n| synonyms = \n''Muscicapa georgiana'' <small>Quoy & Gaimard, 1830</small><br>\n''Eopsaltria leucogaster'' <small>Gould, 1846</small><br>\n''Eopsaltria georgiana'' <small>(Quoy & Gaimard, 1830)</small><br>\n''Quoyornis georgianus warreni'' <small>Mathews, 1916</small><br>\n''Eopsaltria leucogastra'' <small>Gadow, 1883</small><br>\n}}\nThe '''white-breasted robin''' (''Quoyornis georgianus'') is a [[passerine]] bird in the Australasian robin family [[Petroicidae]] and is the only species placed in the genus '''''Quoyornis'''''. It is [[Endemism|endemic]] to [[Southwest Australia|southwestern Australia]]. Unlike many other Australian robins, it lacks bright colours in its plumage, being a predominantly greyish bird with white underparts. Like other closely related Australasian robins, it is a cooperative breeder. It is sedentary, with pairs or small groups maintaining territories.\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe white-breasted robin was first described by the [[France|French]] [[natural history|naturalist]]s, [[Jean Ren\u00e9 Constant Quoy]] and [[Joseph Paul Gaimard]], in 1830, as ''Muscicapa georgiana'',<ref>{{ cite book | last1=Quoy | first1=Jean | author1-link=Jean Ren\u00e9 Constant Quoy | last2=Gaimard | first2=Joseph Paul | author2-link=Joseph Paul Gaimard | editor-last=Dumont d'Urville | editor-first=Jules | editor-link=Jules Dumont d'Urville | year=1830 | title=Voyage de la corvette l'Astrolabe : ex\u00e9cut\u00e9 par ordre du roi, pendant les ann\u00e9es 1826-1827-1828-1829: Zoologie | volume=Volume 1 | language=French |  location=Paris | publisher=J. Tastu | page=175 | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/2064231 }}</ref>{{efn|Although the ornithological section of the ''Voyage de la corvette l'Astrolabe'' has 1830 on the title page, it was not published until 1832,<ref>{{ cite journal | last=Ml\u00edkovsk\u00fd | first=Ji\u0159\u00ed  | year=2012 | title=The dating of the ornithological part of Quoy and Gaimard's \"''Voyage de l'Astrolabe''\"| journal=Zoological Bibliography | volume=2 | issue=2&3 | pages=59-69 | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/54038142 }}</ref>}} taking its name from the site, [[King George Sound]], where the authors had collected specimens.<ref name=\"Lindsey\">{{cite book |last1=Cayley |first1=Neville W. |editor1-last=Lindsey |editor1-first=Terence R. |title=What bird is that?: a completely revised and updated edition of the classic Australian ornithological work |date=2011 |publisher=Australia's Heritage Publishing |location=Walsh Bay, N.S.W. |isbn=978-0-9870701-0-4 |page=65 |edition= Signature|title-link=What Bird is That? }}</ref> It was later described by [[John Gould]] in 1846 as ''Eopsaltria leucogaster'',<ref>{{cite journal |last=Gould | first=John |authorlink=John Gould |year=1846 |title=Descriptions of eleven new species of Australian birds |journal=Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London |volume=14 |issue= |pages= 18\u201321| url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/12862669}}</ref> though as the former took precedence, its specific name remains ''georgiana''.<ref name=afd/> Australian amateur ornithologist, [[Gregory Mathews]], described a paler specimen from [[Warren River (Western Australia)|Warren River]] as a distinct subspecies ''warreni'',<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Mathews |first1=Gregory M. |title=List of additions of new sub-species to, and changes in, my \"List of the Birds of Australia\" |journal=Austral Avian Records |date=1916 |volume=3 |issue=3 |pages=53-68 [59] |url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/33271258}}</ref> though this was not recognised subsequently.<ref name=afd/>\n\nA 2009 genetic analysis of [[nuclear DNA|nuclear]] and [[mitochondrial DNA]] unexpectedly placed the white-breasted robin as sister taxon to the two ''[[Tregellasia]]'' robins native to northeastern Australia.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Multi-locus phylogeny clarifies the systematics of the Australo-Papuan robins (Family Petroicidae, Passeriformes) |author=Loynes, Kate |author2=Joseph, Leo |author3=Keogh, J. Scott|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|volume=53|issue=1|pages=212\u201319|doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2009.05.012 |year=2009 |pmid=19463962}}</ref> This result was confirmed by another [[molecular phylogenetic]] study published in 2011.<ref>{{ cite journal | last1=Christidis | first1=L. | last2=Irestedt | first2=M. | last3=Rowe | first3=D. | last4=Boles | first4=W.E. | last5=Norman | first5=J.A. | year=2011 | title=Mitochondrial and nuclear DNA phylogenies reveal a complex evolutionary history in the Australasian robins (Passeriformes: Petroicidae) | journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution | volume=61 | issue=3 | pages=726-738 | doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2011.08.014 | pmid=21867765}}</ref>\nThe species is now placed in its own genus ''Quoyornis'', which was introduced by  Mathews in 1912.<ref name=ioc>{{cite web| editor1-last=Gill | editor1-first=Frank | editor1-link=Frank Gill (ornithologist) | editor2-last=Donsker | editor2-first=David | year=2019 | title=Australasian robins, rockfowl, rockjumpers, Rail-babbler | work=World Bird List Version 9.2 | url=https://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/au_robins/ | publisher=International Ornithologists' Union | accessdate=15 June 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{ cite journal | last=Mathews | first=Gregory | author-link=Gregory Mathews | year=1912 | title=New generic names for Australian birds | journal=Austral Avian Record | volume=1 | pages=105-117 [111]  | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/33339694 }}</ref> The name combines Quoy's name with the [[Ancient Greek]] ''ornis'' 'bird'.<ref>{{cite web | last=Jobling | first=J.A. | year=2019 | title=''Quoyornis'' | editor1-last=del Hoyo | editor1-first=J. | editor2-last=Elliott | editor2-first=A. | editor3-last=Sargatal | editor3-first=J. | editor4-last=Christie | editor4-first=D.A. | editor5-last=de Juana | editor5-first=E. | work=Handbook of the Birds of the World Alive: Key to Scientific Names in Ornithology | publisher=Lynx Edicions | url=https://www.hbw.com/dictionary/definition/quoyornis | accessdate=17 June 2019 }}</ref> \n\nWhite-breasted robin is the official name given to this species by the  [[International Ornithologists' Union]] (IOC).<ref name=\"ioclist\">{{cite web |editor1-last=Gill |editor1-first=Frank |editor1-link=Frank Gill (ornithologist) |editor2-last=Donsker |editor2-first=David |year=2019 |title=Australasian robins, rockfowl, rockjumpers, Rail-babbler |work=World Bird List Version 9.2 |url=https://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/au_robins/ |publisher=International Ornithologists' Union |accessdate=19 June 2019}}</ref> Although, like all Australian robins, it is not closely related to either the [[European robin]] or the [[American robin]].<ref name=Boles88>{{cite book |title=The Robins and Flycatchers of Australia |last=Boles |first=Walter E.|year=1988 |publisher=Angus & Robertson |location=Sydney |isbn=0-207-15400-7 |pages=119}}</ref> Gould had called it 'white-bellied robin' in 1848, and other terms used included grey-breasted or white-breasted shrike-robin from the late 19th and early 20th centuries. The 'shrike-' prefix was dropped by the RAOU in 1926.<ref name=fraser13>{{cite book|last1=Gray|first1=Jeannie|last2=Fraser|first2=Ian|title=Australian Bird Names: A Complete Guide|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=W1TCqHVWQp0C&pg=PT257|year=2013|publisher=Csiro Publishing|location=Collingwood, Victoria | isbn=978-0-643-10471-6|page=257-258}}</ref> It is known as ''boydjil'' by the local indigenous people of Augusta.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Abbott, Ian | title=Aboriginal names of bird species in south-west Western Australia, with suggestions for their adoption into common usage |year= 2009 |journal= Conservation Science Western Australia Journal |volume= 7 |issue=2 |pages=213\u2013278 [263] |url=http://www.dpaw.wa.gov.au/images/documents/about/science/cswa/articles/14.pdf}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\nThe white-breasted robin ranges between {{convert|14.5|and|17.0|cm|in|frac=4|abbr=on}} long, with a wingspan of {{convert|22-25|cm|in|frac=4|abbr=on}}. The male weighs 20.5 g, while the female is lighter at 16.5 g.{{sfn|Higgins|2002|p=798}} Males and females are similar in coloration, with blue-grey upperparts, paler eyebrows, and whitish underparts. The grey tail is tipped with white. Bills and feet are black in colour, while eyes are dark brown. Birds from the northern part of its range are smaller and darker grey in colour. Juveniles are brownish.<ref name = \"Simpsday\">{{cite book| vauthors = Simpson K, Day N, Trusler P  | title = Field Guide to the Birds of Australia | publisher = Viking O'Neil | year = 1993 | location = Ringwood, Victoria | pages = 392 | isbn = 0-670-90478-3}}</ref>\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nThe white-breasted robin is found in [[Western Australia]] south from [[Geraldton, Western Australia|Geraldton]] to the southwest corner of the continent. Within this area, it is mainly restricted to two areas of different habitat. In the main southern part of its range, it is found in an area bounded by Jarrahdale and [[Wooroloo, Western Australia|Woorooloo]] on or east of the Darling Scarp, and south-east to Beaufort Inlet. Here it occurs in tall forest dominated by karri (''[[Eucalyptus diversicolor]]''), where it is found in dense undergrowth of such plant species as karri hazel (''[[Trymalium odoratissimum]]'' subsp. ''trifidum''), karri she\u2013oak (''[[Allocasuarina decussata]]''), and nedik (''[[Bossiaea aquifolium]]''), typically along rivers and gullies. It also inhabits dry [[sclerophyll]] forest of karri, jarrah (''[[Eucalyptus marginata]]''), and bull banksia (''[[Banksia grandis]]''), where it lives in the 2-3 m high [[understory]]. The northern population is found along a narrow band from Geraldton south to [[Yanchep National Park]], where it lives in coastal thickets\u2014often covered in dodder\u2014of ''[[Acacia rostellifera]]'', ''[[Acacia cyclops]]'', ''[[Melaleuca cardiophylla]]'' growing over sand dunes on limestone soils. It is sedentary, with pairs or small groups maintaining territories in its range. Young male birds remain around their parents' territories as helper birds for around a year, while females disperse.{{sfn|Higgins|2002|p=799}}<!-- cites paragraph -->\n\n==Behaviour==\n[[File:Eopsaltria georgiana -Northcliff, Western Australia, Australia -nest-8.jpg|right|thumb|Nesting in Western Australia]]\nThe white-breasted robin is a cooperative breeder; breeding pairs are often assisted by one or more [[Helpers at the nest|helper]] birds who help raise young.<ref name=\"Russ04\">{{cite journal|vauthors=Russell EM, Brown RJ, Brown MN |year=2004|title=Life history of the white-breasted robin, ''Eopsaltria georgiana'' (Petroicidae), in south-western Australia |journal=Australian Journal of Zoology |volume=52 |issue=2 |pages=111\u201345|doi=10.1071/ZO03049 }}</ref> Helper birds are mostly male; female birds are more likely to leave the territory in the first year of their life, while males are more likely to remain.<ref name=\"Russ04\"/>\n\n===Breeding===\nBreeding season is late winter to early summer with up to two broods raised. The nest is a neat cup made of dry grass, bark, and [[spider web]]s, generally located in a tree-fork in dense scrub close to a watercourse.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = ((Cooney SJN)), Watson DM, Young J | title = Mistletoe nesting in Australian birds: a review | journal = Emu | volume = 106 | pages = 1\u201312\n | publisher = CSIRO Publishing | year = 2006 | url = https://www.anu.edu.au/BoZo/stuart/Papers/MU040181.pdf | doi = 10.1071/MU04018| accessdate = 2007-06-07}}</ref> Two pale olive- to blue-green eggs, often splotched with a darker variant of the background colour, are laid. They measure 16&nbsp;mm x 21&nbsp;mm, and one is often much paler than the other.<ref>{{cite book  | last = Beruldsen  | first = Gordon  | title = Australian Birds: Their Nests and Eggs  | publisher = self  | year = 2003  | location = Kenmore Hills, Qld  | pages = 336\u2013337 | doi = | isbn = 0-646-42798-9}}</ref> Incubation lasts 16 or 17 days, with young leaving the nest two weeks after hatching.<ref name=\"Russ04\"/>\n\n===Feeding===\nThe white-breasted robin is insectivorous, foraging for its prey mainly on or near the ground, in or beneath undergrowth.{{sfn|Higgins|2002|p=799}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Cited text===\n* {{cite book |title=[[Handbook of Australian, New Zealand and Antarctic Birds]]. Volume 6: Pardalotes to Shrike-thrushes |editor1=Higgins, Peter J. |editor2=Peter, Jeffrey M. |year=2002 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Melbourne |isbn=0-19-553762-9| ref={{sfnRef|Higgins|2002}} }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Eopsaltria georgiana}}\n*[http://ibc.hbw.com/ibc/phtml/especie.phtml?idEspecie=6886 Internet Bird Collection - videos of white-breasted robin]\n\n{{Petroicidae}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q116147}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:robin, white-breasted}}\n[[Category:Endemic birds of Southwest Australia]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1832|white-breasted robin]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Species of songbird native to southwestern Australia}}\n{{speciesbox\n| name = White-breasted robin\n| image = Eopsaltria georgiana -Denmark, Western Australia, Australia-8.jpg\n| image_caption = In Western Australia\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22704860/0 |title=''Eopsaltria georgiana'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Quoyornis\n| parent_authority = [[Gregory Mathews|Mathews]], 1912\n| species = georgianus\n| authority = ([[Jean Ren\u00e9 Constant Quoy|Quoy]] & [[Joseph Paul Gaimard|Gaimard]], 1832)\n| synonyms_ref = <ref name=afd>{{cite web|url=https://biodiversity.org.au/afd/taxa/Eopsaltria_%28Quoyornis%29_georgiana |title=Species ''Eopsaltria'' (''Quoyornis'') ''georgiana'' (Quoy & Gaimard, 1830)|author=Australian Biological Resources Study|date=12 June 2010 |work=Australian Faunal Directory|publisher=Department of the Environment, Water, Heritage and the Arts, Australian Government|accessdate=19 June 2019}}</ref>\n| synonyms = \n''Muscicapa georgiana'' <small>Quoy & Gaimard, 1830</small><br>\n''Eopsaltria leucogaster'' <small>Gould, 1846</small><br>\n''Eopsaltria georgiana'' <small>(Quoy & Gaimard, 1830)</small><br>\n''Quoyornis georgianus warreni'' <small>Mathews, 1916</small><br>\n''Eopsaltria leucogastra'' <small>Gadow, 1883</small><br>\n}}\nThe '''white-breasted robin''' (''Quoyornis georgianus'') is a [[passerine]] bird in the Australasian robin family [[Petroicidae]] and is the only species placed in the genus '''''Quoyornis'''''. It is [[Endemism|endemic]] to [[Southwest Australia|southwestern Australia]]. Unlike many other Australian robins, it lacks bright colours in its plumage, being a predominantly greyish bird with white underparts. Like other closely related Australasian robins, it is a cooperative breeder. It is sedentary, with pairs or small groups maintaining territories.\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe white-breasted robin was first described by the [[France|French]] [[natural history|naturalist]]s, [[Jean Ren\u00e9 Constant Quoy]] and [[Joseph Paul Gaimard]], in 1830, as ''Muscicapa georgiana'',<ref>{{ cite book | last1=Quoy | first1=Jean | author1-link=Jean Ren\u00e9 Constant Quoy | last2=Gaimard | first2=Joseph Paul | author2-link=Joseph Paul Gaimard | editor-last=Dumont d'Urville | editor-first=Jules | editor-link=Jules Dumont d'Urville | year=1830 | title=Voyage de la corvette l'Astrolabe : ex\u00e9cut\u00e9 par ordre du roi, pendant les ann\u00e9es 1826-1827-1828-1829: Zoologie | volume=Volume 1 | language=French |  location=Paris | publisher=J. Tastu | page=175 | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/2064231 }}</ref>{{efn|Although the ornithological section of the ''Voyage de la corvette l'Astrolabe'' has 1830 on the title page, it was not published until 1832,<ref>{{ cite journal | last=Ml\u00edkovsk\u00fd | first=Ji\u0159\u00ed  | year=2012 | title=The dating of the ornithological part of Quoy and Gaimard's \"''Voyage de l'Astrolabe''\"| journal=Zoological Bibliography | volume=2 | issue=2&3 | pages=59-69 | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/54038142 }}</ref>}} taking its name from the site, [[King George Sound]], where the authors had collected specimens.<ref name=\"Lindsey\">{{cite book |last1=Cayley |first1=Neville W. |editor1-last=Lindsey |editor1-first=Terence R. |title=What bird is that?: a completely revised and updated edition of the classic Australian ornithological work |date=2011 |publisher=Australia's Heritage Publishing |location=Walsh Bay, N.S.W. |isbn=978-0-9870701-0-4 |page=65 |edition= Signature|title-link=What Bird is That? }}</ref> It was later described by [[John Gould]] in 1846 as ''Eopsaltria leucogaster'',<ref>{{cite journal |last=Gould | first=John |authorlink=John Gould |year=1846 |title=Descriptions of eleven new species of Australian birds |journal=Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London |volume=14 |issue= |pages= 18\u201321| url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/12862669}}</ref> though as the former took precedence, its specific name remains ''georgiana''.<ref name=afd/> Australian amateur ornithologist, [[Gregory Mathews]], described a paler specimen from [[Warren River (Western Australia)|Warren River]] as a distinct subspecies ''warreni'',<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Mathews |first1=Gregory M. |title=List of additions of new sub-species to, and changes in, my \"List of the Birds of Australia\" |journal=Austral Avian Records |date=1916 |volume=3 |issue=3 |pages=53-68 [59] |url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/33271258}}</ref> though this was not recognised subsequently.<ref name=afd/>\n\nA 2009 genetic analysis of [[nuclear DNA|nuclear]] and [[mitochondrial DNA]] unexpectedly placed the white-breasted robin as sister taxon to the two ''[[Tregellasia]]'' robins native to northeastern Australia.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Multi-locus phylogeny clarifies the systematics of the Australo-Papuan robins (Family Petroicidae, Passeriformes) |author=Loynes, Kate |author2=Joseph, Leo |author3=Keogh, J. Scott|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|volume=53|issue=1|pages=212\u201319|doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2009.05.012 |year=2009 |pmid=19463962}}</ref> This result was confirmed by another [[molecular phylogenetic]] study published in 2011.<ref>{{ cite journal | last1=Christidis | first1=L. | last2=Irestedt | first2=M. | last3=Rowe | first3=D. | last4=Boles | first4=W.E. | last5=Norman | first5=J.A. | year=2011 | title=Mitochondrial and nuclear DNA phylogenies reveal a complex evolutionary history in the Australasian robins (Passeriformes: Petroicidae) | journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution | volume=61 | issue=3 | pages=726-738 | doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2011.08.014 | pmid=21867765}}</ref>\nThe species is now placed in its own genus ''Quoyornis'', which was introduced by  Mathews in 1912.<ref name=ioc>{{cite web| editor1-last=Gill | editor1-first=Frank | editor1-link=Frank Gill (ornithologist) | editor2-last=Donsker | editor2-first=David | year=2019 | title=Australasian robins, rockfowl, rockjumpers, Rail-babbler | work=World Bird List Version 9.2 | url=https://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/au_robins/ | publisher=International Ornithologists' Union | accessdate=15 June 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{ cite journal | last=Mathews | first=Gregory | author-link=Gregory Mathews | year=1912 | title=New generic names for Australian birds | journal=Austral Avian Record | volume=1 | pages=105-117 [111]  | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/33339694 }}</ref> The name combines Quoy's name with the [[Ancient Greek]] ''ornis'' 'bird'.<ref>{{cite web | last=Jobling | first=J.A. | year=2019 | title=''Quoyornis'' | editor1-last=del Hoyo | editor1-first=J. | editor2-last=Elliott | editor2-first=A. | editor3-last=Sargatal | editor3-first=J. | editor4-last=Christie | editor4-first=D.A. | editor5-last=de Juana | editor5-first=E. | work=Handbook of the Birds of the World Alive: Key to Scientific Names in Ornithology | publisher=Lynx Edicions | url=https://www.hbw.com/dictionary/definition/quoyornis | accessdate=17 June 2019 }}</ref> \n\nWhite-breasted robin is the official name given to this species by the  [[International Ornithologists' Union]] (IOC).<ref name=\"ioclist\">{{cite web |editor1-last=Gill |editor1-first=Frank |editor1-link=Frank Gill (ornithologist) |editor2-last=Donsker |editor2-first=David |year=2019 |title=Australasian robins, rockfowl, rockjumpers, Rail-babbler |work=World Bird List Version 9.2 |url=https://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/au_robins/ |publisher=International Ornithologists' Union |accessdate=19 June 2019}}</ref> Although, like all Australian robins, it is not closely related to either the [[European robin]] or the [[American robin]].<ref name=Boles88>{{cite book |title=The Robins and Flycatchers of Australia |last=Boles |first=Walter E.|year=1988 |publisher=Angus & Robertson |location=Sydney |isbn=0-207-15400-7 |pages=119}}</ref> Gould had called it 'white-bellied robin' in 1848, and other terms used included grey-breasted or white-breasted shrike-robin from the late 19th and early 20th centuries. The 'shrike-' prefix was dropped by the RAOU in 1926.<ref name=fraser13>{{cite book|last1=Gray|first1=Jeannie|last2=Fraser|first2=Ian|title=Australian Bird Names: A Complete Guide|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=W1TCqHVWQp0C&pg=PT257|year=2013|publisher=Csiro Publishing|location=Collingwood, Victoria | isbn=978-0-643-10471-6|page=257-258}}</ref> It is known as ''boydjil'' by the local indigenous people of Augusta.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Abbott, Ian | title=Aboriginal names of bird species in south-west Western Australia, with suggestions for their adoption into common usage |year= 2009 |journal= Conservation Science Western Australia Journal |volume= 7 |issue=2 |pages=213\u2013278 [263] |url=http://www.dpaw.wa.gov.au/images/documents/about/science/cswa/articles/14.pdf}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\nThe white-breasted robin ranges between {{convert|14.5|and|17.0|cm|in|frac=4|abbr=on}} long, with a wingspan of {{convert|22-25|cm|in|frac=4|abbr=on}}. The male weighs 20.5 g, while the female is lighter at 16.5 g.{{sfn|Higgins|2002|p=798}} Males and females are similar in coloration, with blue-grey upperparts, paler eyebrows, and whitish underparts. The grey tail is tipped with white. Bills and feet are black in colour, while eyes are dark brown. Birds from the northern part of its range are smaller and darker grey in colour. Juveniles are brownish.<ref name = \"Simpsday\">{{cite book| vauthors = Simpson K, Day N, Trusler P  | title = Field Guide to the Birds of Australia | publisher = Viking O'Neil | year = 1993 | location = Ringwood, Victoria | pages = 392 | isbn = 0-670-90478-3}}</ref>\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nThe white-breasted robin is found in [[Western Australia]] south from [[Geraldton, Western Australia|Geraldton]] to the southwest corner of the continent. Within this area it is mainly restricted to two areas of different habitat. In the main southern part of its range, it is found in an area bounded by Jarrahdale and [[Wooroloo, Western Australia|Woorooloo]] on or east of the Darling Scarp, and south-east to Beaufort Inlet. Here it occurs in tall forest dominated by karri (''[[Eucalyptus diversicolor]]''), where it is found in dense undergrowth of such plant species as karri hazel (''[[Trymalium odoratissimum]]'' subsp. ''trifidum''), karri she\u2013oak (''[[Allocasuarina decussata]]'') and nedik (''[[Bossiaea aquifolium]]''), typically along rivers and gullies. It also inhabits dry [[sclerophyll]] forest of karri, jarrah (''[[Eucalyptus marginata]]'') and bull banksia (''[[Banksia grandis]]''), where it lives in the 2-3 m high [[understory]]. The northern population is found along a narrow band from Geraldton south to [[Yanchep National Park]], where it lives in coastal thickets\u2014often covered in dodder\u2014of ''[[Acacia rostellifera]]'', ''[[Acacia cyclops]]'', ''[[Melaleuca cardiophylla]]'' over sand dunes on limestone soils. It is sedentary, with pairs or small groups maintaining territories in its range. Young male birds remain around their parents' territories as helper birds for around a year while females disperse.{{sfn|Higgins|2002|p=799}}<!-- cites paragraph -->\n\n==Behaviour==\n[[File:Eopsaltria georgiana -Northcliff, Western Australia, Australia -nest-8.jpg|right|thumb|Nesting in Western Australia]]\nThe white-breasted robin is a cooperative breeder; breeding pairs are often assisted by one or more [[Helpers at the nest|helper]] birds who help raise young.<ref name=\"Russ04\">{{cite journal|vauthors=Russell EM, Brown RJ, Brown MN |year=2004|title=Life history of the white-breasted robin, ''Eopsaltria georgiana'' (Petroicidae), in south-western Australia |journal=Australian Journal of Zoology |volume=52 |issue=2 |pages=111\u201345|doi=10.1071/ZO03049 }}</ref> Helper birds are mostly male; female birds are more likely to leave the territory in the first year of their life, while males are more likely to remain.<ref name=\"Russ04\"/>\n\n===Breeding===\nBreeding season is late winter to early summer with up to two broods raised. The nest is a neat cup made of dry grass, bark, and [[spider web]]s, generally located in a tree-fork in dense scrub close to a watercourse.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = ((Cooney SJN)), Watson DM, Young J | title = Mistletoe nesting in Australian birds: a review | journal = Emu | volume = 106 | pages = 1\u201312\n | publisher = CSIRO Publishing | year = 2006 | url = https://www.anu.edu.au/BoZo/stuart/Papers/MU040181.pdf | doi = 10.1071/MU04018| accessdate = 2007-06-07}}</ref> Two pale olive- to blue-green eggs, often splotched with a darker variant of the background colour, are laid. They measure 16&nbsp;mm x 21&nbsp;mm, and one is often much paler than the other.<ref>{{cite book  | last = Beruldsen  | first = Gordon  | title = Australian Birds: Their Nests and Eggs  | publisher = self  | year = 2003  | location = Kenmore Hills, Qld  | pages = 336\u2013337 | doi = | isbn = 0-646-42798-9}}</ref> Incubation lasts 16 or 17 days, with young leaving the nest two weeks after hatching.<ref name=\"Russ04\"/>\n\n===Feeding===\nThe white-breasted robin is insectivorous, foraging for its prey mainly on or near the ground, in or beneath undergrowth.{{sfn|Higgins|2002|p=799}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Cited text===\n* {{cite book |title=[[Handbook of Australian, New Zealand and Antarctic Birds]]. Volume 6: Pardalotes to Shrike-thrushes |editor1=Higgins, Peter J. |editor2=Peter, Jeffrey M. |year=2002 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Melbourne |isbn=0-19-553762-9| ref={{sfnRef|Higgins|2002}} }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Eopsaltria georgiana}}\n*[http://ibc.hbw.com/ibc/phtml/especie.phtml?idEspecie=6886 Internet Bird Collection - videos of white-breasted robin]\n\n{{Petroicidae}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q116147}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:robin, white-breasted}}\n[[Category:Endemic birds of Southwest Australia]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1832|white-breasted robin]]\n", "name_user": "Rogermccart", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDistribution and habitat:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/White-breasted_robin"}
